Introduction

I recently completed my Google Data Analytics Certificate coursework, and to encapsulate my experience learning data analysis techniques, I decided to complete a case study analyzing the relationship between environment, social and governance (ESG) data with happiness on both a country-specific and region basis. I will be using RStudio to prepare, process and analyze the correlations between various ESG indicators and happiness rankings on a regional basis. I will be following the ask, prepare, process, analyze, share, act steps of the data analytics process.

Ask

Hypothetical scenario: The World Bank recently published data on 17 key sustainability themes spanning environmental, social, and governance categories, and want to know how they relate to happiness around the world. Although the World Happiness Report already provides information on GDP per capita, social support, healthy life expectancy, freedom to make life choices, generosity, and perceptions of corruption, the World Bank wishes to further contextualize these categories with their ESG data. The questions that the World Bank would like to be answered to better guide their sustainability themes are:

  1. How does income inequality relate to happiness?

  2. How do measures of gender parity and happiness relate to each other?

  3. How does health relate to happiness?

  4. How can we make people happier?

Prepare

For this analysis, I will be using both the World Banks Environment, Social And Governance Dataset which you can find here and the Sustainable Development Solutions Networks World Happiness Report database, which you can find here. First, I downloaded and previewed the ESG dataset, Happiness dataset, along with packages that I would use in my analysis.

Process and Analyze

After looking at the structure of the ESG dataset on R and the Happiness datasets on Excel, I decided to convert each dataset if necessary to wide format, split both datasets up into years, and merge them year by year.

I also decided to focus on a few key variables from the datasets that can act as proxy variables for the questions asked by the World Bank. For the inequality question, there were no direct measures of inequality in the ESG dataset, so I decided to use the GDP per Capita measure in the Happiness dataset to compare against countries happiness scores. For the second question, I used the life expectancy measures in both datasets to ensure consistency between the datasets, and included mortality rates for children under 5 and undernourishment rates in the ESG dataset. For the third question, I decided to look at comparisons of women in national parliaments, female to male labor force participation, and gender parity in school enrollment rates as proxies for gender equity. I next created a subset of the ESG dataset containing these relevant variables.

new1_ESG <- ESG[3268:16970, c(1, 3, 4, 60, 61, 62, 63, 64)]
new2_ESG <- subset(new1_ESG,`Indicator Code`=='SP.DYN.LE00.IN'|`Indicator Code` == 'SH.DYN.MORT' | `Indicator Code` == 'SN.ITK.DEFC.ZS' | `Indicator Code` == 'SG.GEN.PARL.ZS' | `Indicator Code` == 'SL.TLF.CACT.FM.ZS' | `Indicator Code` == 'SE.ENR.PRSC.FM.ZS')
new3_ESG <- new2_ESG[,-c(3)] %>%  #removing code names because the happiness index doesn't have codes
  rename(Country = `Country Name`) %>%
  rename(Indicator = `Indicator Name`)
#Creating separate tables for each year, with the same format as the Happiness datasets
ESG_2019 <- new3_ESG[,c(1,2,7)] %>%
  dcast(Country  ~ Indicator,value.var="2019")
ESG_2018 <- new3_ESG[,c(1,2,6)] %>%
  dcast(Country  ~ Indicator,value.var="2018")
ESG_2017 <- new3_ESG[,c(1,2,5)] %>%
  dcast(Country ~ Indicator, value.var = "2017")
ESG_2016 <- new3_ESG[,c(1,2,4)] %>%
  dcast(Country ~ Indicator, value.var = "2016")
ESG_2015 <- new3_ESG[,c(1,2,3)] %>%
  dcast(Country ~ Indicator, value.var = "2015")

For reference, the exact indicators that correspond to the codes mentioned above are:

  • SP.DYN.LE00.IN = Life expectancy at birth, total (years)
  • SH.DYN.MORT = Mortality rate, under-5 (per 1,000 live births)
  • SN.ITK.DEFC.ZS = Prevalence of undernourishment (% of population)

I used these measurements in relation to the gender question.

  • SG.GEN.PARL.ZS = Proportion of seats held by women in national parliaments (%)
  • SL.TLF.CACT.FM.ZS = Ratio of female to male labor force participation rate (%) (modeled ILO estimate)
  • SE.ENR.PRSC.FM.ZS = School enrollment, primary and secondary (gross), gender parity index (GPI)

Analyze (Cont.) and Share

As a reminder, these are the questions the World Bank gave as their business task: 1) How does income inequality relate to happiness?

  1. How do measures of gender parity and happiness relate to eachother?

  2. How does health relate to happiness?

  3. How can we make people happier?

To tackle the first question, lets begin by looking at the relationship between income inequality and happiness through capturing the correlation between GDP per Capita and Happiness in 2019.

require(devtools)
install_version("ggplot2", version = "2.2.1", repos = "http://cran.us.r-project.org")
## rlang  (1.1.2  -> 1.1.3 ) [CRAN]
## digest (0.6.33 -> 0.6.34) [CRAN]
library(ggplot2)
library(hrbrthemes)
ggplot(data = Final, aes(x = GDP_Cap_2019, y = H_Score_2019,))+
  labs(title = "Inequality and Happiness in 2019", x = "GDP per
       Capita", y = "Happiness Score", colour = "Region") + geom_point(aes(colour = Region.y), show.legend = TRUE) +
   geom_smooth(method=lm , color="red", se=FALSE) +
  theme_ipsum()

As seen by the scatter plot, there is a strong positive relationship between GDP per Capita and Happiness. Additionally, Sub-Sarahan African countries seem to have the lowest of both GDP per Capita and Happiness, while Australia and New Zealand have both a high GDP per Capita and Happiness Score. Does this result remain consistent for the years 2015-2018?

Finally, lets look at the relationship between health and happiness, starting with 2015. I first create a dataset with the variables specific to health and happiness for 2015.

Health_2015 <- Final %>% 
  rename(Life_Expectancy = "Life expectancy at birth, total (years).x") %>%
  rename(Child_Mortality = "Mortality rate, under-5 (per 1,000 live births).x")%>%
  rename(Undernourishment = "Prevalence of undernourishment (% of population).x")%>%    
  select(H_Score_2015, Life_Exp_2015, Life_Expectancy,
         Child_Mortality, Undernourishment)
ggcorr(Health_2015, label=TRUE) + labs(title = "Health and Happiness in 2015")

There are much stronger correlations here. As a sanity check, the life expectancy measure used in the World Happiness dataset and the World Bank dataset should match, and they do. Lets explore some of these relationships more in detail:

Act

The World Happiness Report was designed to advocate for happiness and well-being as a tenet for social policy. This analysis reveals greater insight in the relationship between happiness and three factors:

  1. income inequality

  2. gender parity, and

  3. health.

As seen by our analysis, the measures of gender parity I used from the ESG datasets did not correlate strongly to happiness across the 2015-2019 time period. However, there was a strong correlation between income inequality and happiness, as well as health and happiness. Therefore, based on the results of this analysis, effective recommendations to answer the World Banks fourth question and make people happier include:

  1. focus on improving health outcomes, especially life expectancy and child mortality. Through the correlation plots for 2015-2019, we see a strong relationship between these two factors and happiness. Therefore, investing in policies to reduce the rate of child mortality and to increase life expectancy are crucial to increase happiness.

  2. increase global incomes, and reduce income inequality. GDP per capita measures both income inequality, and the average income of people in countries across the globe. Increasing worker productivity through greater educational measures, encouraging more women to enter the workforce, and government investment in capital can increase GDP and GDP per capita.

Through using the World Banks ESG data to contextualize and further explore how societies can be happier, we have a deeper insight on policies that can effectively increase happiness across the world. This concludes my case study. I hope you learned something new and saw some cool visualizations!
